04843nam a22005775i 9780822392446DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223924467 a10.1515/97808223924462doi  a(DE-B1597)553791  a(OCoLC)841915438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS664.T33 2009 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a305.5/6095991 aTadiar, Neferti X. M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThings Fall Away :bPhilippine Historical Experience and the Makings of Globalization /cNeferti X. M. Tadiar; Fredric Jameson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (496 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Loosed Upon the World -- tOne. Prostituted Filipinas and the Crisis of Philippine Culture -- tTwo. Women Alone -- tThree. Poetics of Filipina Export -- tFour. Modern Refuse in the ''City of Man'' -- tFive. Petty Adventures in (the Nation's) Capital -- tSix. Metropolitan Debris -- tSeven. Revolutionary Imagination and the Masses -- tEight. Guerilla Passion and the Unfinished Cultural Revolution -- tNine. The Sorrows of People -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Things Fall Away, Neferti X. M. Tadiar offers a new paradigm for understanding politics and globalization. Her analysis illuminates both the power of Filipino subaltern experience to shape social and economic realities and the critical role of the nation's writers and poets in that process. Through close readings of poems, short stories, and novels brought into conversation with scholarship in anthropology, sociology, politics, and economics, Tadiar demonstrates how the devalued experiences of the Philippines' vast subaltern populations-experiences that "fall away" from the attention of mainstream and progressive accounts of the global capitalist present-help to create the material conditions of social life that feminists, urban activists, and revolutionaries seek to transform. Reading these "fallout" experiences as vital yet overlooked forms of political agency, Tadiar offers a new and provocative analysis of the unrecognized productive forces at work in global trends such as the growth of migrant domestic labor, the emergence of postcolonial "civil society," and the "democratization" of formerly authoritarian nations.Tadiar treats the historical experiences articulated in feminist, urban protest, and revolutionary literatures of the 1960s-90s as "cultural software" for the transformation of dominant social relations. She considers feminist literature in relation to the feminization of labor in the 1970s, when between 300,000 and 500,000 prostitutes were working in the areas around U.S. military bases, and in the 1980s and 1990s, when more than five million Filipinas left the country to toil as maids, nannies, nurses, and sex workers. She reads urban protest literature in relation to authoritarian modernization and crony capitalism, and she reevaluates revolutionary literature's constructions of the heroic revolutionary subject and the messianic masses, probing these social movements' unexhausted cultural resources for radical change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aGlobalizationzPhilippines. 0aNational characteristics, Philippine. 0aWomenzPhilippines. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392446zCo-access DOI >> cli